└────────┘ └────────┘ └────────┘
Architectural Components:

Central Cloud — Consists of RegionOne (physical platform management region) and System Controller (central management of subcloud addition, synchronization, alarm monitoring, and updates)
Subclouds — StarlingX instances that host containerized applications. Simplex, Duplex, Standard, and any deployment can be configured. Authenticate with a local Identity Provider (Keystone, K8s Service Accounts) for autonomy and performance
Subcloud status: Managed (synchronize immediately after setting change, normal operation) / Unmanaged (queue for setting changes, use during local maintenance, alarms will continue to be sent)
Network:

The subcloud connects to the System Controller through OAM Network + Management Network (or Admin Network) L3
All System Controller ↔ Subcloud messaging uses admin REST API endpoint (HTTPS), certificates are automatically managed internally
Autonomy:

Synchronized distributed control plane reduces latency
Autonomous control plane: All subcloud local services are up and running even if Northbound connectivity to the central region is lost.
Each subcloud handles its own authentication locally, so there is no service interruption in the event of a central connection failure
3.7 Data Networks
출처: https://docs.starlingx.io/datanet/kubernetes/data-network-management-data-networks.html, https://docs.starlingx.io/introduction/terms.html, https://docs.starlingx.io/node_management/kubernetes/node_interfaces/interface-settings.html

StarlingX data network management models the L2 network connected to the node interface and is a key factor in optimizing the performance of data traffic in the edge cloud.

Define key concepts
Application Network	The higher-level network that the container or VM uses for actual service traffic (e.g., K8s pod network, 5G vDU Fronthaul traffic network)
Data Network	An underlying L2 connection that lays the foundation for the application network to operate. Acting as a bridge between physical NICs and virtual networks
Physical Networks	OSI refers to the entire physical hardware infrastructure, including L1 (cable) + L2 (physical switch/Ethernet)
VLAN (Virtual LAN)	A method of isolating and operating multiple logical L2 networks by assigning a virtual identifier (802.1Q Tag) on top of a single physical L2 network band.
Interface Classes
There are three main classes that you assign to interfaces for handling data traffic:

data: An interface that connects to a virtual switch (vSwitch). It communicates through a software bridge and is used for general cloud traffic processing.
pci-passthrough: Assign physical NIC hardware directly to specific containers/VMs. Performance is maximized by not going through an intermediate software layer, but it cannot be shared because it uses hardware exclusively.
pci-sriov: A method of splitting a physical NIC into multiple virtual functions (VFs). High-performance communication is possible while multiple applications share hardware directly (essential for high-performance workloads such as 5G vRAN).
SR-IOV (RootI/O Virtualization) is a hardware virtualization technology that allows a single physical PCIe device (e.g., NIC) to be used as multiple logical devices.

5G vDU deployment example
Port 1 (pci-sriov): Set to pci-sriov class→ create 8 VFs → Multiple vDU containers each receive VFs to handle Fronthaul traffic (ultra-low latency)
Port 2 (data): Set to data class → manage → via vSwitch· Handling OAM traffic (regular traffic)
Data Network 유형
flat: A simple data network that maps 1:1 to the physical network
VLANs: Operate by isolating multiple logical networks on top of a single physical network using VLAN IDs
CLI Implementation and Architecture (system command)
system datanetwork-list The same command is based on the userspace daemon (Service), not the kernel:

CLI (cgts-client): Interprets user-entered commands and converts them into REST API requestssystem
API (sysinv-api): The API server operating on the Controller node receives the request
Backend (sysinv-conductor): The key daemon that handles the actual business logic
DB (PostgreSQL): Writes configuration information to persistent storage
Result: The daemon dynamically injects and manages network settings on each host based on the DB information.sysinv
Network Topology View (GUI)
The Admin > Platform > Data Network Topology menu in the Horizon web interface provides a graphical view of the physical and logical connection status between the data network and the worker host.

Key CLI Commands
# Data Network 생성
system datanetwork-add <name> <type>        # type: flat, vlan

# Data Network 목록 조회
system datanetwork-list

# 인터페이스에 Data Network 할당
system interface-datanetwork-assign <hostname> <ifname> <datanetwork-name>
How to set up SR-IOV (CLI)
If you want to specify the number of VFs with the interface in the pci-sriov class, use the -c pci-sriov and -N <numvfs> options. The typical order is as follows.system host-if-modify

Host lock (when Worker/Standard configured; AIO-SX can be omitted)
system host-lock <hostname>
Set interface classes and VF counts
system host-if-modify -n <ifname> -m <mtu> -c pci-sriov -N <numvfs> [--vf-driver=netdevice|vfio] <hostname> <ethname>
-c pci-sriov: Set the interface class to pci-sriov
-N <numvfs>: Number of VFs to create (e.g. 8)
--vf-driver=netdevice: Exposed from a container to a common network device (suitable for defaults, vDU, etc.)
--vf-driver=vfio: When using DPDK, etc.
<ethname>: physical port name (e.g. enp1s0f0). Confirmed bysystem host-if-list -a <hostname>
Data Network 연결 (선택)
system interface-datanetwork-assign <hostname> <ifname> <datanetwork-name>
Unlock the Host
system host-unlock <hostname>
Example (port enp1s0f0 set to pci-sriov, 8 VFs, data network datanet-fronthaul connection):

system host-lock compute-0
system host-if-modify -m 1500 -n sriov1 -c pci-sriov -N 8 --vf-driver=netdevice compute-0 enp1s0f0
system interface-datanetwork-assign compute-0 sriov1 datanet-fronthaul
system host-unlock compute-0
