5.2 Host Profiles: Standard vs Low-Latency
출처: https://docs.starlingx.io/node_management/index-node-mgmt-cd0f9d8eaee6.html, https://docs.starlingx.io/deploy/index-deploy-da06a98b83b1.html, https://docs.starlingx.io/node_management/kubernetes/changing-a-worker-host-performance-profile.html

All hosts can be configured with the following profiles, depending on the kernel selection:

Standard	Use the default kernel. Ideal for typical data throughput-driven workloads
Low-Latency	preempt-rt Based on the use of a real-time kernel. Ideal for workloads such as 5G vRAN that require ultra-low latency
1. Scope of the profile
The stated profile is applied to the "StarlingX Host OS (Worker Host Kernel)" itself, which is the underlying (bottom) rather than the inside of the K8s Pod that rises on top of it.

Only when the Host OS is powered by a real-time kernel can the K8s pods created on top of it be guaranteed true end-to-end ultra-low latency performance through 1:1 pinning and isolation of CPU cores.preempt-rt
2. Internal behavior when changing profiles
Rather than changing a single configuration file, the entire kernel layer is reversed through a change in the logical set of Sysinv DB.

Boot image replacement: The standard kernel is replaced with a dedicated kernel (e.g., ) compiled boot image.CONFIG_PREEMPT_RTvmlinuz-*-rt-amd64
Disable CPU watchdog: Disable the Per-CPU scheduler watchdog () to prevent kernel timer interrupts from interfering with real-time tasks. (This increases the kernel fault detection time)nmi_watchdog=0
Enhanced Core Isolation: When assigning a specific CPU core to a function, boot parameters such as , and are automatically injected, completely blocking the Host kernel from occupying that core for thread/timer purposes.Isolatednohz_fullrcu_nocbskthread_cpus
Increased power consumption: To optimize latency, certain cores are prevented from entering C-State (sleep mode), resulting in significant power consumption regardless of CPU occupancy.
