7. Security Architecture
출처: https://docs.starlingx.io/security/kubernetes/index-security-kub-81153c1254c3.html, https://docs.starlingx.io/security/index-security-84d0d8aa401b.html#kubernetes

StarlingX's security architecture refers to a specialized security system that is enforced and integrated at the platform level to protect distributed edge cloud environments, in addition to the basic security features provided by typical Linux or Kubernetes (RBAC, Secure Boot, hardware vulnerability patching, etc.).

7.1 Kernel and OS layer security: Transparent intranet encryption (IPsec)
StarlingX provides built-in kernel-level encryption to protect multi-node communication that is geographically distributed or easily exposed at the infrastructure floor level.

IPsec (Forced Encryption): The daemon controls the network stack (XFRM) of the Linux kernel. The entire traffic to and from the distributed system, such as the controller and the worker node, is encrypted by snatching the packet directly from the kernel end just before the packet leaves the LAN card (NIC).strongSwan
Features: Even if the K8s app transmits the network in plaintext on top of it, there is no need for separate application security settings with "transparent encryption" encryption that is forcibly encrypted from the OS floor.
7.2 Application and Platform Layer Security (System Apps Integrated Security Controls)
To overcome the limitations of simple K8s basic functions (Secret, NetworkPolicy, etc.), StarlingX packages security components in the form of system apps, which are deployed and managed at the time of initial bootstrapping.

Enforce Container Image Integrity (Portieris)

It is an open-source signature verifier led by IBM, and the container runtime intervenes via K8s webhook communication before the image is launched.
Unified management of platform-wide certificates (cert-manager-based automation)

Centrally control the certificate issuance and renewal lifecycle of all touchpoints essential to the operation of cluster systems, including StarlingX REST API, web dashboard (GUI), and OAM network communication.
cert-manager daemon (container) manages Certificate resources
Auto-renew before expiration and inject into that service
자동화된 시크릿 금고 통합 (HashiCorp Vault & Barbican)

Integrated HashiCorp Vault (for K8s) and Barbican (API repository for platforms such as BMC passwords) to address vulnerabilities in plaintext storage
In particular, StarlingX's Vault-manager container automatically handles the complex initialization and unlocking (unsealing) of the Vault server, simplifying the operational phase for edge environments.
Pod-level AppArmor profile global automation

While AppArmor itself is a regular Linux kernel feature, StarlingX integrates the Security Profiles Operator daemon to make it easier to handle in the K8s environment.
Security Profiles Operator
define AppArmor (and Seccomp) profiles as K8s resources (e.g. SecurityProfile),
The Operator synchronizes the profile to each node and concatenates it with a nnotation of the pod, as if "this pod uses this profile".
Starl ingX adds Horizon (web dashboard) to it, allowing you to apply and synchronize container defense profiles for each node, active/inactive, and edge-specific container defense profiles to many nodes with a single click.
